The user updates his self-description as follows: I now gravitate to band-driven, rhythm‑forward recordings — punchy basslines, angular guitar riffs, crisp propulsive drums and vintage/new‑wave synth textures. I enjoy production that is polished or stylized when it heightens groove, atmosphere, and tight ensemble interplay; vocals that sit confidently in the mix with attitude rather than intimate close‑mic whisper; concise, hook‑led arrangements and dynamic sequencing that reward repeated plays.
I still favor strong melodies, emotionally literate, story‑minded lyrics, varied arrangements between tracks, and transparent instrumental detail and informative liner notes that deepen listening. I appreciate clear timbre and defined room/ambient cues when they serve the song.
I dislike overly thin, purely acoustic singer‑songwriter mixes that feel like isolated demos; bedroom‑close vocal presentation that flattens energy; saccharine or blandly polished production that removes rhythmic drive; and homogenized mastering that kills punch and stereo definition.

The positive CD has the following updated information: Tight band‑driven New Wave; punchy bass, angular guitars, crisp propulsive drums and vintage/new‑wave synth textures; stylized production with confident, mid/forward vocals, hook‑led arrangements, dynamic sequencing and mastering that preserves punch and stereo width—ideal for listeners craving rhythmic drive and ensemble interplay.

